metadata.name: Unfolded #148
metadata.description:
A plane is repeatedly folded over itself, choosing creases either at random, or according to some pattern (like a grid). These creases form the boundaries of the individual textured tiles.

Once the folds are complete, they are undone in reverse order, recreating the original plane. With each unfolding, the orientation of each crease (as a mountain or a valley), and each tile (facing up or down) is recorded as a sequence of 1s and 0s. Tiles are colored and textured according to similarities in these binary sequences, giving rise to subtle symmetries and repetitions.

Written in vanilla JS & HTML5 Canvas.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Elevation #40
metadata.description:
Thereâ€™s so much more to our world than what we are able to perceive, let alone understand. Will we ever be able to even fully understand ourselves?

â€“

Elevation is a series of 320 generative elevation drawings of imaginary structures. It is a reminder of the limits of our consciousness, and an ode to the manifold nuances that lie beyond what we can perceive, beyond what we even can imagine.

As a generative artist, I aim to elevate my own consciousness with the help of the machine. I welcome algorithms and randomness into the creation of my works, taking full control, and intentionally giving it away, always seeking to expand my imagination. For as humans alone, we remain limited to our own edifice of thought, and often fail to free ourselves from the visible, mundane world.

Both are present in Elevation: the visible and the imaginary, the mundane and the transcendent, the solid and the fragile. Where an architectâ€™s elevation drawing marks the transition from the thought world into the visible world, Elevation remains in-between, depicting both the idea of an imaginary structure, and the structure itself.

â€“

Elevation is intended for print. All holders of an Elevation NFT will be able to order the corresponding signed print in the respective paper format via andreasrau.eu/elevation. Press [s] to save the image as displayed or [p] to generate a print-ready PNG image at 300 dpi. This might take a while, depending on paper format and your hardware.

â€“

Elevation
p5.js, glsl, html, css
Andreas Rau, 2022

metadata.description:
Back when I was a researcher at a human-computer interaction lab, I parked in the adjacent neighborhood and rode the city bus into campus.

Usually this was a pretty uneventful affair.

One spring day though, the bus was packed and I had to stand right up front by the driver. Despite trying to appear busy enough not to be bothered, the driver struck up a conversation.

At some point in the short trip, we stopped at a red light. It was then that he made an off-hand comment that I've remembered ever since.

â€œThe moment between when the light turns green and when I realize it, thatâ€™s where my soul resides.â€

Iâ€™m not sure how youâ€™re supposed to respond to that. But nevertheless it smacked me.

Do consider them an expended shard of my soul and the culmination of experiences that have led up to this moment.

metadata.name: Step by Step #26
metadata.description:
Step by Step explores the feeling of being stuck, confined - walking the path ahead of you often only seeing the immediate next step until exhaustion. We all feel this way from time to time â€” in our lives, jobs, bodies, situations â€” yet in our search for something, we shouldn't forget that there can still be beauty along the path.

The project takes some inspiration from Henri Matisse, both in the aesthetics of his later works (i.e. the "Cut Outs") and metaphorically in the sense that he had underwent medical treatment which left him wheelchair- or bed-bound towards the later part of his life, forcing him to give up painting, yet in his exploration of this new creative medium which involved cutting paper and pinning them up, his unorthodox work went on to become the most transformative of his career.

Released as part of the 4th edition of the CureÂ³ Parkinson's cure fundraiser exhibition organized by Artwise Curators and Bonhams as part of a specially comissioned selection of generative artists minting NFTs, curated by Foteini Valeonti and Alex Estorick with the support of fx(hash) at Bonhams, London from 13-17th January 2023.

metadata.name: #2023Streams #61
metadata.description:
#2023Streams is a color theory study that explores the use of algorithmically-generated color palettes and the juxtaposition of color harmonies keyed on a common hue. It brings playfulness to experimentation through the use of randomized features that control lighting, color assortment, and more, to create interesting, vibrant compositions.

I consider this pieceâ€”my generative "genesis"â€”to be a preliminary "sketch" whose desired outcomes are insights into color and light that might be applied to more advanced projects in the future.

This piece is also a first step for me, into the world of professional art. An art school dropout and software engineer by profession, I've been hacking on generative art projects, games, and interactive experiences for more than two decades. But now, in 2023, it's my time to focus and prioritize art and creativity.

Each image can be modified using the following keyboard commands:
- [d] Download the rendered image
- [j] Toggle between "jungle" (dimensional) and "jazz" (flat) modes
- [l] Toggle between light and dark backgrounds
- [e] Toggle between curved (ellipse) and flat (rectangle) shapes
- [s] Enable/disable shadows and highlights
- [t] Enable/disable transparency

Each image is rendered at 2400 x 2400 pixels by default. This should be suitable for an 8" x 8" output (at 300 dpi). Should you desire a higher resolution output, the image can be magnified up to 6x by clicking the "open â†—ï¸" link and appending a density parameter to the URL, e.g. `&density=4` 

Lastly, #2023Streams is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license. This license allows reusers to distribute, remix, adapt, and build upon the material in any medium or format, so long as attribution is given to the creator. The license allows for commercial use.

What does this license mean? It means I invite you to have fun with your new piece, get creative and bring something new into the world.

I hope you enjoy these outputs as much as I do. Thank you for stopping byâ€”and hopefully collecting.

metadata.name: A Pile, To Be Sorted #22
metadata.description:
Compartmentalization in service of clarity.
Dedicated to my Dad and, by extension, his advice.

When I get overwhelmed (which is often), I typically call my dad. Heâ€™s always got some relatable story from his life Iâ€™ve never heard before, OR he hits me with the same piece of advice heâ€™s been giving me for as long as I can remember:

â€œOf course itâ€™s hard to stay calm when you look at the pile in front of you. Every responsibility, want and obligation, is not something weâ€™re meant to face all at once. Break it up, take on one task from the pile, and focus on that.â€

This has been such a stable pattern that I often donâ€™t need to hear him say it. Iâ€™ll finish describing whatâ€™s going on and stop him before he can even start, so he doesnâ€™t have to waste his breath on something I should know by now, itâ€™s already helping just to remember it.

The best thing I can do for myself is to pick something out of the pile and handle it in isolation. I find that often each task will grow the pile exponentially. Itâ€™s easy to handle my health and fitness when thatâ€™s all I have to think about. But then I have to think about finances, maintaining friendships, taking care of my plants, dating, and finding time for a hobby. Each one of those things has its own nuances and complications. With all that in mind, going to the gym sounds overwhelming.

Butâ€” Going to the gym is easy. Pick one thing, focus, get it done, and watch the pile shrink. Repeat.

Iâ€™ve opted to create a design which illustrates this overwhelm and demonstrates how quickly those individual tasks lose form in the pile.

Press 's' to save a .png
Press '1', '2', or '3' to change render size
Press 't' to toggle linen texture (for use printing onto textured paper or cloth)

Created by Chris McCully in October 2023 using p5.js, chroma.js, and GLSL

metadata.name: Garden, Monoliths #14
metadata.description:
"Garden, Monoliths" is the result of an algorithm that started in April 2021. It was called "Grass.js".
Spring was blooming all around the house, taking over the stones and remnants of ancient battles that stood here. Inspiration was everywhere.
The initial goal was to use mathematical formulas for creating patterns inspired by the density of nature, that could be used by a pen plotter, so it kept focusing on outputting vector lines. This history and practice produced a graphical style based on line strokes, plus occasionally some transparent, filled shapes.
Each artwork will be either "Garden" or "Monolith", for they are variations of two existing designs from the workshop.
